column13:
Taz Deserves Applause

I have to come to the very edge of Aurora, Colorado in a tiny strip mall to get a true taste of India. I ignore the tear in the leather booth when the aroma of steamed vegetables and a dozen unknown spices flood my nostrils. Vegetable MoMo ($4.99) is placed in the center of the table. Evenly plated in a circle on what looks like a cheap Ikea plate, my eagerness takes over as the steam rises. The roof of my mouth quickly resents my impatience, but I tell myself, &#34;Worth it.&#34; 
Fifteen minutes pass as the Bollywood music videos play on the television before the main event of Chicken Korma ($12.99) arrives. With the first bite of the most tender meat and creamy, perfectly recognizable korma sauce, I feel elated that I didn&#39;t fill my stomach with only the Veggie MoMo. The chicken must have marinated for weeks with how easily my teeth tore into the flesh. The rice soaks up every bit of this bright orange sauce mirroring the color of the walls. From my three months of living in Bangalore, India, I never imagined I&#39;d find a place this familiar in atmosphere or food as perfectly prepared and accurate to the cuisine of a country half way around the world. To finish this impeccable déjà vu, I order the most popular dessert in India, Gulab Jamun ($3.99), &#34;Deep fried milk balls soaked in saffron flavored syrup, served hot,&#34; as the menu states, and hot it is. 
The only obvious Americanization I noticed belong to the labeling under &#34;Drinks.&#34; The chai was labeled &#34;Chai Tea.&#34; Any Indian would laugh at this statement simply because chai actually means tea. I&#39;m sure this was just to make it easier for us Americans, but I giggle to myself, saying, &#34;Tea tea.&#34; 
Way past my limit of fullness, I finish the last bite of this classic dessert, gathering as much syrup as I can fit on my teaspoon. If this establishment were closer, my paycheck would be lost to this small business every week.

So we ordered dinner to go tonight...didn&#39;t think to check the food to make sure the order was correct (because people usually only have to do that at Burger King) so that was our fault...

However we get home and realize that they gave us pork fried rice after we asked for steamed rice. My daughter is allergic to the onions that are in the rice which is the reason we ALWAYS ask for white rice wherever we go. We get home (20 mins later) and call them to see if there&#39;s anything they can do to compensate for THEIR mistake....their response &#34;we are closing, you can bring the food in tomorrow and we&#39;ll switch the rice out&#34;

Wow...wrong on so many levels. Anybody in their right mind can come up with at least 3 reasons why that was a terrible response! Won&#39;t be eating here again. There&#39;s another location on Peoria and 6th.

Most of all, they use soda, so you end up &#34;airy.&#34; 

As for the choice, buffet spread - good food, oily, some items not the freshest (the seasoned yogurt rice seemed coarse, not soft, which makes me think it&#39;s not fresh rice). The Rasam (tomato soup like dish) was LOADED with oil...floating! The okra was a blessing, saving grace! The Vada was OILY.

I&#39;ve experienced better vegetarian buffet. authentic ones too, so this doesn&#39;t do it! For Aurora, it&#39;s good.

My bf and I went for dinner and happy hour.. i had the bean enchilada with rice and salad and I forgot what he had but the plate was soooo hot ... That means the microwaved the food.
The enchilada was soo disgusting flavorless and it wasn&#39;t that hot the cheese was old.. The only thing I ate was the rice beans and salad. The drinks were weakk. They noticed we barley touched the food and only charged us for the 2 drinks.

if I was given the opportunity I would be a chef at this restaurant and help create a new menu. :)
